headline_main: Coronavirus, State of the Union, Iowa: Your Wednesday Briefing

abstract: FARMINGTON, N.H. — Across New Hampshire on Tuesday, voters expressed a range of reactions to the Iowa meltdown: everything from anger to ambivalence. A few voters said they felt bad for Iowans and Democratic officials there. And several admitted that although they had been tracking developments in Iowa, they went to sleep as soon as it became clear that the results would not come in overnight.
lead_paragraph: FARMINGTON, N.H. — Across New Hampshire on Tuesday, voters expressed a range of reactions to the Iowa meltdown: everything from anger to ambivalence. A few voters said they felt bad for Iowans and Democratic officials there. And several admitted that although they had been tracking developments in Iowa, they went to sleep as soon as it became clear that the results would not come in overnight.
headline_main: N.H. voters wonder ‘how do you not practice for something like this?’

abstract: HAMPTON, N.H. — At an afternoon stop at a pizzeria here a group of climate activists holding signs reading “make fossil fuel execs pay” sprang up in the crowd and interrupted Pete Buttigieg as he was discussing the need to address the issue.

abstract: A first wave of results showed Pete Buttigieg and Bernie Sanders with an early lead, with Joseph R. Biden Jr. well behind.
snippet: A first wave of results showed Pete Buttigieg and Bernie Sanders with an early lead, with Joseph R. Biden Jr. well behind.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — Democratic officials in Iowa on Tuesday provided a measure of clarity to the muddled outcome of its statewide caucuses, releasing a delayed first wave of partial results that showed Pete Buttigieg and Senator Bernie Sanders with a preliminary lead and former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. falling well behind the other top-tier candidates.

abstract: KEENE, N.H. — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts called on the Iowa Democratic Party to “get it together,” saying the reporting errors that upended caucus results threatened to damage trust in the democratic process.
lead_paragraph: KEENE, N.H. — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts called on the Iowa Democratic Party to “get it together,” saying the reporting errors that upended caucus results threatened to damage trust in the democratic process.

headline_main: Warren urges the Iowa Democratic Party to ‘get it together.’

abstract: How a political ritual turned into a political nightmare.
snippet: How a political ritual turned into a political nightmare.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — Every four years the Iowa caucuses are supposed to deliver the first clear signal of which candidates are actually resonating with voters. That didn’t happen on Monday.

headline_main: Picturing Chaos at the Iowa Caucuses

abstract: Billionaire Michael Bloomberg is doubling the already massive amount of money he will spend on advertising, an effort to lift his Democratic presidential bid and capitalize on the chaotic outcome of Monday's Iowa caucuses.

lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Billionaire Michael Bloomberg is doubling the already massive amount of money he will spend on advertising, an effort to lift his Democratic presidential bid and capitalize on the chaotic outcome of Monday's Iowa caucuses.
headline_main: Bloomberg Doubles Ad Spending After Chaos of Iowa Caucuses
headline_print_headline: Bloomberg Doubles Ad Spending After Chaos of Iowa Caucuses

abstract: The political universe has been turned upside down by the failure of the Iowa caucuses. Traditionally the event provides the first concrete tally after months of speculation about the presidential primary. But Monday night's Democratic caucuses ended inconclusively as the state party blamed technological problems for preventing it from reporting results. Here are some questions and answers about what happened — and what might come next.
